05211nam a22007695i 9780801461873DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20112011nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808014618737 a10.7591/97808014618732doi  a(DE-B1597)535277  a(OCoLC)1129173832  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aSOC0070002bisacsh04a323.6/31 aSmith, Michael Peter, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCitizenship across Borders :bThe Political Transnationalism of El Migrante /cMatt Bakker, Michael Peter Smith. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2011] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (264 p.) :b4 maps, 9 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tAcronyms -- tPart 1. Setting the Stage -- t1. The Politics of Transnational Citizenship -- t2. Reconstructing the Migrant in Mexican State-Policy Discourse -- tPART 2. The Politics of Transnational Community Development -- t3. The Regional State and the Politics of Translocality -- t4. The Social Construction of "Migrant-Led Productive Investment" -- tPart 3. El Migrante as Transnational Citizen -- t5. Transnational Electoral Politics: The Multiple Coronations of the "Tomato King" -- t6. Institutionalizing New Spaces for Migrant Political Agency: Votary Ser Votado in Mexico -- tPart 4. The Two Faces of Transnational Citizenship -- t7. The Second Face of Transnational Citizenship: Migrant Activists Recross the Border -- t8. The Boundaries of Citizenship: Transnational Power Revisited -- tAppendix Transnational Ethnography: Methods, Fieldwork, and Subjects -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMichael Peter Smith and Matt Bakker spent five years carrying out ethnographic field research in multiple communities in the Mexican states of Zacatecas and Guanajuato and various cities in California, particularly metropolitan Los Angeles. Combining the information they gathered there with political-economic and institutional analysis, the five extended case studies in Citizenship across Borders offer a new way of looking at the emergent dynamics of transnational community development and electoral politics on both sides of the border. Smith and Bakker highlight the continuing significance of territorial identifications and state policies—particularly those of the sending state—in cultivating and sustaining transnational connections and practices. In so doing, they contextualize and make sense of the complex interplay of identity and loyalty in the lives of transnational migrant activists. In contrast to high-profile warnings of the dangers to national cultures and political institutions brought about by long-distance nationalism and dual citizenship, Citizenship across Borders demonstrates that, far from undermining loyalty and diminishing engagement in U.S. political life, the practice of dual citizenship by Mexican migrants actually provides a sense of empowerment that fosters migrants' active civic engagement in American as well as Mexican politics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aCitizenshipzMexico. 0aCitizenshipzUnited States. 0aImmigrantsxPolitical activityzUnited States. 0aMexican AmericansxPolitics and government. 0aTransnationalismxPolitical aspectszMexico. 0aTransnationalismxPolitical aspectszUnited States. 4aLatino/A Studies. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 4aSociology & Social Science. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Emigration & Immigration.2bisacsh1 aBakker, Matt, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591